{{speciesbox | name = Greater big-footed mouse | status = EN | status_system = IUCN3.1 | status_ref = <ref name=IUCN /> | genus = Macrotarsomys | species = ingens | authority = (Petter, 1959) | range_map = Macrotarsomys ingens range map.svg | range_map_caption = Greater big-footed mouse range }}
The '''greater big-footed mouse''' or '''long-tailed big-footed mouse''' (''Macrotarsomys ingens'') is a [[nocturnal]] [[rodent]] found only in north west [[Madagascar]]. It was [[Species description|first described]] by F. Petter in 1959.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Petter, F. |year=1959 |title=Un nouveau rongeur de Madagascar (Nesomyinae) : ''Macrotarsomys ingens'' nov. sp. |journal=Mammalia |volume=23 |issue=2 |pages=139 |doi=10.1515/mamm.1959.23.2.139 }}</ref> It is listed as an endangered species as a result of habitat loss.
==Description== The greater big-footed mouse grows to a head and body length of up to {{convert|15|cm|0|abbr=on}} with an even longer tail of up to {{convert|24|cm|0|abbr=on}}. Its weight is {{convert|50|to|60|g}} and it has large eyes and large oval ears. Its big feet are adapted for climbing among the branches of trees. The pelage is brownish-fawn with a greyish undercoat; the underparts and legs are creamy white.<ref name=ARKive>{{cite web |url=http://www.arkive.org/greater-big-footed-mouse/macrotarsomys-ingens/ |title=Greater big-footed mouse (''Macrotarsomys ingens'') |work=ARKive |accessdate=2013-01-07}}</ref>
==Distribution and habitat== The greater big-footed mouse is found only in Mahajanga Province in north-western Madagascar, in the Ankarafantsika forest which is now part of the [[Ankarafantsika National Park]].<ref name=IUCN/> This is a low rainfall area with typical dry tropical vegetation. The mouse is a nocturnal species. It spends the day in a burrow in the forest floor, the entrance of which is concealed under a rock or tree root and spends the night scrambling about in bushes and trees looking for food.<ref name=ARKive/>
==Biology== The greater big-footed mouse is believed to be [[Herbivore|herbivorous]] and probably eats berries, fruit, nuts, seeds, roots, and stems. It probably falls prey to such [[Predation|predators]] as [[snake]]s, [[bird]]s and [[Carnivore|carnivorous]] [[mammal]]s.<ref name=ARKive/><!--explain why these are only "believed" and "probably"?-->
==Status== The greater big-footed mouse is listed as "[[Endangered]]" in the [[IUCN Red List of Threatened Species]]. This is because, although it is fairly common in the area in which it is found, its total range amounts to a single block of less than {{convert|5000|km2}}. Its habitat is subject to degradation by fire and logging and the mouse is at risk of predation by [[feral]] animals.<ref name=IUCN>{{cite web |url=http://www.iucnredlist.org/details/12646/0 |title=''Macrotarsomys ingens'' |author1=Goodman, S. |author2=Rakotondravony, D. |author3=Dollar, L. |date=2008 |work=IUCN Red List of Threatened Species. Version 2012.2 |accessdate=2013-01-08}}</ref>
